Jean Seeland What is Red Shift and Why it Occurs?   In cosmological scales, redshifts have two main causes: peculiar motion and the expansion of the universe.  Peculiar motion is when the light source is in fact moving due to, for example, gravitational attraction. For instance, galaxies orbiting the center of mass of a cluster. This is similar to the Doppler effect that happens in sound. Note that blueshift is also possible here: objects can move closer to the observer.  Now, redshifts can also be caused by the expansion of the universe. This happens not because there is a relative motion between the two objects, but because the distance between them has increased (due to expansion). This is only perceived at very large scales and can be used with other tools to determine the rate of expansion of the universe.  jk
